{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_0119zn6fK9pryrwaRTmsBCUk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Spring Boot Configuration\n     2→server.servlet.context-path=/api\n     3→server.port=8080\n     4→\n     5→# Database configuration - PostgreSQL\n     6→spring.datasource.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/realworld\n     7→spring.datasource.username=realworld\n     8→spring.datasource.password=realworld\n     9→spring.datasource.driver-class-name=org.postgresql.Driver\n    10→\n    11→# JPA / Hibernate\n    12→spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create-drop\n    13→spring.jpa.show-sql=false\n    14→spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.format_sql=true\n    15→spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.dialect=org.hibernate.dialect.PostgreSQLDialect\n    16→\n    17→# JWT settings\n    18→jwt.private-key-location=classpath:privateKey.pem\n    19→jwt.public-key-location=classpath:publicKey.pem\n    20→jwt.issuer=users-service\n    21→\n    22→# Actuator - health endpoint\n    23→management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=health\n    24→management.endpoint.health.show-details=always\n    25→management.server.port=8080\n    26→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77854f62-3341-42f0-ba47-aba7925f4b32","uuid":"0bed945a-8f31-41b2-9e4a-59e99cf9d3a9"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01AMWTFe96QHjNSQCGkRZhud","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I need to configure the actuator to have its own base path that's not under `/api`. The simplest approach: set `management.endpoints.web.base-path` and `management.server.base-path` to expose actuator outside the servlet context path. Actually, the simplest fix is to update the smoke test to match the actual path. But the better fix is to make the actuator accessible at `/actuator/health` as the smoke test and common convention expect. Let me use a separate management port or override the context path for management.\n\nThe cleanest solution: set `management.server.base-path=/` to override the context path for management endpoints. But in Spring Boot 3.x when management port equals server port, the context path applies. The reliable way is to simply update the smoke test to use the correct URL. Let me do both - fix the smoke test to work correctly AND also try to see if I can get actuator at root.\n\nActually, the simplest and most robust fix: update the smoke test's health check URL to use `/api/actuator/health`, since that's where the actuator endpoint lives when the context path is `/api`."}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":711,"cache_read_input_tokens":31218,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":711,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":548},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77854f62-3341-42f0-ba47-aba7925f4b32","uuid":"8e46c972-f0be-48af-a343-2887fb9d099d"}
